# Onion / Ports-and-Adapters Architecture

All application code follows a strict layered architecture. Dependencies point inward only.

## Layer structure

```
src/
  domain/         # Core domain — entities, value objects, domain services, ports (interfaces)
  application/    # Use cases / application services — orchestrates domain objects
  adapters/       # Adapter implementations — storage, UI, external integrations
```

## Rules

1. **`domain/` has zero external dependencies.** No imports from `application/`, `adapters/`, or any framework/library. Only TypeScript built-ins and other `domain/` modules.
2. **Ports live in `domain/`.** Repository interfaces, service interfaces, and any integration boundary the domain needs are defined as TypeScript interfaces in `domain/`.
3. **`application/` depends on `domain/` only.** Application services import domain entities, ports, and domain services. They never import from `adapters/`.
4. **`adapters/` implements ports.** Concrete classes in `adapters/` implement the interfaces defined in `domain/`. Adapters may import from `domain/` and `application/`, and may use external libraries.
5. **Dependency injection wires it together.** A composition root (e.g., `src/main.ts` or `src/bootstrap.ts`) instantiates adapters and injects them into application services. Domain code never instantiates its own dependencies.

## Import direction summary

```
adapters/ → application/ → domain/
              ↑ never reversed
```

## Common mistakes

- ❌ Domain entity importing a database client or ORM
- ❌ Domain service importing from `adapters/`
- ❌ Application service instantiating a concrete adapter instead of accepting a port
- ✅ Domain defines `ExpenseRepository` interface; `adapters/storage/IndexedDbExpenseRepository` implements it
